'''Dong Hyun Kim''' (born May 1973)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08106545/officers |title=WASABI SUSHI BENTO LIMITED - Officers (free information from Companies House) |website=Beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |date=15 June 2012 |accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> is a UK-based Korean businessman, the founder of the chains [[Wasabi (restaurant)|Wasabi]], [[Kimchi|Kimchee]] and Kimchee To Go.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joe Lutrario |url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/Business/Business-Profile-Kimchee |title=Business Profile: Kimchee |website=Bighospitality.co.uk |date=13 May 2013 |accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref name="telegraph1">{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Ben |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/leisure/11805016/Wasabi-returns-to-profit-after-US-expansion.html |title=Wasabi returns to profit after US expansion |publisher=Telegraph |date=15 August 2015 |accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/articles/369036/wasabi-to-open-20-more-sites-after-25m-funding-deal |title=Wasabi to open 20 more sites after £25m funding deal |website=Thecaterer.com |date= |accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref>

Kim moved to the UK in 1999.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140225202125/http://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/wasabi-heads-big-apple] </ref> Kim, who had been a market trader in [[Camden Town|Camden]], London, founded Wasabi in 2003, with the first branch opening on London's Embankment.<ref name="telegraph1"/>

