{{Infobox person | name = Frank Hasenfratz | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{bya|1935}} | birth_place = [[Szár]], Hungary | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date†|birth date†}} --> | death_place = | residence = [[Guelph]], Ontario, Canada | nationality = Canadian | other_names = | occupation = Businessman | title = Chairman, [[Linamar]] | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | net worth = US$1.0 billion (2015)<ref name="Forbes profile">{{cite web |title=Forbes profile: Frank Hasenfratz |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/frank-hasenfratz-1/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref> | spouse = Margaret | children = 2 daughters, including [[Linda Hasenfratz|Linda]] }}
'''Frank Hasenfratz''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born 1935) is a Hungarian-born Canadian [[billionaire]] businessman, the founder and owner of the car parts maker [[Linamar]].
==Early life== Hasenfratz was born in 1935 in [[Szár]], Hungary.<ref>[https://www.gerillaoneletrajz.hu/blog/linamar-sztori/ András Baráth - Linamar – ismerd meg a Magyarországon is aktív multinacionális vállalat magyar alapítójának történetét]</ref> He left Hungary in May 1957 and arrived in [[Quebec City]], Canada, after the failed [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-05-21/hungarian-refugee-becomes-car-parts-billionaire-in-canada |title=Hungarian Refugee Becomes Car Parts Billionaire in Canada |author=Hugo Miller |date=21 May 2014 |website=Bloomberg LP |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>
==Career== He started a one-man machine shop in his basement in 1964, and then incorporated in 1966 under the name [[Linamar]] after his two daughters [[Linda Hasenfratz|Linda]] (current Linamar [[CEO]]), Nancy and his wife Margaret.<ref name="Forbes profile"/>
As of 2015, the company now employed 19,000 people at 45 plants, and it is from Hasenfratz's 23.6% stake in the company, plus share sales, dividends, and other asset groupings that he had a net worth of approximately $1 billion.<ref name="Forbes profile"/>
==Honours== In 2014, he was made a member of the [[Order of Canada]] "for his contributions to Canada’s manufacturing industry and for his philanthropic initiatives".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=16037&t=12&ln=Hasenfratz|title=The Governor General of Canada|first=The Office of the Secretary to the Governor|last=General|date=|website=gg.ca|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>
==Personal life== Hasenfratz is married to Margaret.<ref name="Forbes profile"/> They have two daughters, [[Linda Hasenfratz|Linda]] and Nancy, and live in [[Guelph]], Ontario, Canada.<ref name="Forbes profile"/>
